  "prompt": "Given 9 digits to work with, how many possible combinations of 3 digits are there?",
  "response": "With 9 digits to choose from and wanting to create a combination of 3 digits, you can use the formula for combinations, which is denoted as \"n choose k\" or C(n,k). In this case, n=9 and k=3.\n\nThe formula is:\n\nC(n,k) = n! / [k! * (n-k)!]\n\nWhere \"!\" denotes factorial, which is the product of all positive integers up to that number.\n\nSo, for our specific case:\n\nC(9,3) = 9! / [3! * (9-3)!]\n       = 9! / [3! * 6!]\n       = (9 \u00d7 8 \u00d7 7 \u00d7 6 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 4 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1) / [(3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1) \u00d7 (6 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 4 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1)]\n       = 362880 / (6 \u00d7 720)\n       = 362880 / 4320\n       = 84\n\nSo, there are 84 possible combinations of 3 digits that can be made from a set of 9 digits.",
